ACCIDENT STATISTICS

Mr. Church:

For a return showing the number of Canadians killed by (a) motor cars on the highway; (b) drowning; (c) accidents at level crossings; (d) ﬁres in homes, showing number injured; (e) other acci- dents, showing number injured.

Mr. Howe: It will be observed that no period of time is mentioned in the question. The government will of course be glad to bring down the information, but there should be a limit to the period to which it shall apply. Perhaps my hon. friend will let me know.

Mr. Church: The bureau of statistics can give the information.

Mr. Howe: Does the hon. member want the information for 1948? If he will indicate his desire in that regard, I shall be glad to carry out the request.

Inquiries of the Ministry ALCOHOLIC LIOUORS

QUESTION AS T0 INQUIRY BY ROYAL COMMISSION

On the orders of the day:

Mr. M. J. Caldwell (Rosetown-Biggar): May I ask a question of the Prime Minister which has some relation to the motion for papers made by the hon. member for Broadview (Mr. Church)? Has the government been asked to appoint a royal commission to investigate the liquor problem in all its aspects, but with par- ticular reference to highway accidents? If so, will the Prime Minister say whether such a royal commission will be set up?

Right Hon. L. S. St. Laurent (Prime Min- ister): To the ﬁrst part of the question the answer is in the affirmative. To the second part of the question the answer is that the representations made to the committee of cabinet have not yet been brought before council for consideration, but that will be done at the earliest opportunity.

fax, is to be appointed the maritime repre- sentative on this committee.

Mr. E. D.
